						<div class="entry">

							<h1 class="post-title single"><a href="http://energyfanatics.com/2009/04/11/how-to-cook-without-oil/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to How to Cook Without Oil">How to Cook Without Oil</a></h1>

							<div class="meta single">

	<span class="meta-author">
		<a href="http://energyfanatics.com/author/PL/" title="Posts by PL Chang" rel="author">PL Chang</a> | 
	</span>

	<span class="meta-date">
		Last updated on <time datetime="2013-08-25">August 25th, 2013</time> |
		Published on April 11, 2009	</span> 

		<span class="meta-comments">
		 | <a href="http://energyfanatics.com/2009/04/11/how-to-cook-without-oil/#comments" rel="bookmark" title="Comments for How to Cook Without Oil">Reply</a>
	</span>
	
</div>
							
							<p>Most people had been conditioned to think that cooking food without oil does not taste good. In reality, food cooked without oil can taste just as good or even better. In fact, many five star or high class restaurants cook their food with little or no oil.</p>
<p>The food industry has convinced most people to believe that conventional vegetable oil is healthy. Their marketing strategy is so successful that it made them billions in a short amount of time. Conventional vegetable oil is one of the worst refined food to consume, because it is 100 percent fat and is devoided of nutrients. Plus, most vegetable oil contains genetically modified substances. Vegetable oil contains high levels of unhealthy saturated fat which stimulates your liver to produce more cholesterol than your body needs. It is important to know that not all saturated fats are bad. The saturated fats found in pasture-raised animals and organic food are actually good for you. These fats are essential for normal cell function.</p>
<p><strong>Sautéing tips to reduce oil</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Use water instead of oil to cook your food. Cook at lower temperatures to prevent the water from evaporating too quickly, this will also prevent the food from sticking to the pan. Using a non-stick pan will also help prevent stickiness.</li>
<li>If you do not like using water, use other substitutes, such as: sherry, vegetable stock, fruit juice (apple juice is a good one), wine, vinegar or low-sodium Tamari sauce (soy sauce). Cook at low or medium heat to prevent them from evaporating too quickly.</li>
<li>For baking food, use any pureed fruit to coat the pan. Pureed bananas, pureed prunes, applesauce and baby food purees are good examples.</li>
<li>If you are going to use oil, only use organic oil or raw oil that has not gone through a heat treating process and is free of harmful synthetic chemicals. These types of oils are actually good for you because they are essential for normal cell function. A great organic oil I recommend using to cook food is called <a href="http://www.shareasale.com/r.cfm?u=233447&amp;b=428278&amp;m=44341&amp;afftrack=&amp;urllink=www%2Esunburstsuperfoods%2Ecom%2Fartisana%2Dorganic%2Draw%2Dcoconut%2Doil%2F" target="_blank">Artisana Raw Organic Coconut Oil</a>.</li>
</ul>
<p>By practicing the tips above daily, you will really start to notice how vibrant and delicious food is. The food will taste more natural and your will have more energy. If you allow your body to adjust to this new way of cooking food, you may not want to go back to the traditional way of cooking.</p>
